; now.fk — clock as a native, sibling-verified by SHAPE not VALUE.
;
; preludes: (none)
;
; Every richer "freshness" walk — capability tokens that expire, ping
; stamps that mean "right now", heartbeat tables that age, async
; correlation windows — has been parked at the same gap: no sibling
; kernel exposes a (now) native. The closest existing primitive is
; file_mtime, which reads an mtime off disk — useful for caching,
; useless for "right now". 42-ping documents the gap explicitly; this
; sample closes it.
;
; The shape we commit to:
;   (now_unix_ms)  → int, milliseconds since 1970-01-01T00:00:00Z
;
; Three sibling kernels (Go, Rust, TypeScript) each register the same
; native — same name, same arity, same return shape. But the VALUE
; differs by definition: each kernel reads its own host clock at its
; own instant of invocation, and even on the same host the three
; processes run sequentially, so the timestamp drifts microseconds
; (sometimes more) between siblings.
;
; Sibling parity therefore CAN'T check the exact value. It checks the
; SHAPE: every kernel returns a positive int, every kernel's int is
; greater than a recent past epoch (1700000000000 = 2023-11-14 UTC,
; chosen well before the band's authoring date). The verdict is the
; sum of these shape checks, which IS sibling-stable because every
; kernel sees the same booleans.
;
; Walk:
;   1. Call (now_unix_ms) twice — capture two timestamps t1, t2.
;   2. Check each is > 0 (any sane unix-ms must be positive).
;   3. Check each is > 1700000000000 (any sane current-era clock).
;   4. Print only the booleans — never the timestamps themselves.
;   5. Verdict: 4 = (t1>0) + (t2>0) + (t1>epoch) + (t2>epoch).

(do
    ;; Two clock reads — the actual ms values diverge between kernels
    ;; and between calls, but the shape verdict is stable.
    (let t1 (now_unix_ms))
    (let t2 (now_unix_ms))

    ;; Recent-past epoch: 2023-11-14T22:13:20.000Z. Any clock that
    ;; matters today is comfortably past this; any clock that isn't
    ;; (uninitialized embedded host, broken VM, RTC reset to 1970)
    ;; would fail the second check while still passing the first.
    (let epoch 1700000000000)

    (let t1-positive (if (gt t1 0) 1 0))
    (let t2-positive (if (gt t2 0) 1 0))
    (let t1-after-epoch (if (gt t1 epoch) 1 0))
    (let t2-after-epoch (if (gt t2 epoch) 1 0))

    (print "t1-positive:" t1-positive)
    (print "t2-positive:" t2-positive)
    (print "t1-after-epoch:" t1-after-epoch)
    (print "t2-after-epoch:" t2-after-epoch)

    ;; Verdict: 4 = two positivity checks + two epoch checks.
    (add t1-positive
         (add t2-positive
              (add t1-after-epoch t2-after-epoch))))
